
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `edit` (ya `nano`, `vim`, etc.) baraye baz kardan va tagheer dadan file-ha-ye matni (text files) estefade mishavad.  Agar dastoor `edit` be tore mostaghim kar nakard, az `nano`, `vim`, ya `emacs` estefade konid. In dastoor-ha ham kargar hastand vali shayad dastoor-ha-ye bishtari dashte bashand.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `edit filename` --> 📝 Baz kardane file ba name `filename`.
    🔹 `nano filename` --> 🚀 Baz kardane file ba estefade az `nano`, yek virayeshgar-e sade.
    🔹 `vim filename` --> 🛠️ Baz kardane file ba estefade az `vim`, yek virayeshgar-e pishrafte (advanced).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ edit myfile.txt

    🔹 Baz kardane file-e `myfile.txt` baraye virayesh.

    $ nano newfile.txt

    🔹 Baz kardane file-e jadid `newfile.txt` baraye virayesh ba `nano`. Agar file vojood nadashte bashad, `nano` aan ra misazad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ edit config.txt
    (ya $ nano config.txt)

    🔹 Baz kardane file-e `config.txt` baraye tagheer dadane tanzeemaat (settings).  Pas az virayesh, tagheerat ra zakhire (save) va az virayeshgar kharej shavid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `edit` command (or `nano`, `vim`, etc.) is used to open and modify text files. If the `edit` command doesn't work directly, use `nano`, `vim`, or `emacs`. These are editors that accomplish the same task but might have more features.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `edit filename` --> 📝 Open the file named `filename`.
    🔹 `nano filename` --> 🚀 Open the file using `nano`, a simple editor.
    🔹 `vim filename` --> 🛠️ Open the file using `vim`, an advanced editor.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ edit myfile.txt

    🔹 Open the file `myfile.txt` for editing.

    $ nano newfile.txt

    🔹 Open a new file `newfile.txt` for editing using `nano`. If the file doesn't exist, `nano` will create it.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ edit config.txt
    (or $ nano config.txt)

    🔹 Open the file `config.txt` to change the settings. After editing, save the changes and exit the editor.

